Note:
Darwin ARM64 (macOS Apple Silicon) System Call Definitions

Defines all system call numbers, platform metadata, and registration logic for
macOS/Darwin running on ARM64 (Apple Silicon: M1, M2, M3, M4 series).

Darwin ARM64 uses the same syscall numbers as Darwin x86_64 (both are XNU
kernel, same syscalls.master table). The difference is the calling convention:
- x86_64: RAX=number, RDI/RSI/RDX/R10/R8/R9=args, syscall instruction
- ARM64:  X16=number, X0-X5=args, svc #0x80 instruction

The 0x2000000 (Unix class) prefix is still applied to syscall numbers.
Errors are signaled via the carry flag on both architectures.

Syscall convention (Darwin ARM64):
- Syscall number in X16 (with 0x2000000 prefix for Unix class)
- Arguments in X0, X1, X2, X3, X4, X5
- Return value in X0
- Error signaled via carry flag (C flag set means error, X0 contains errno)
- Invoked via: svc #0x80

Reference: XNU kernel bsd/kern/syscalls.master (same table for both archs)
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/platforms/platform_interface.runa" as PlatformInterface
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/syscall_registry.runa" as SyscallRegistry
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Darwin ARM64 Syscall Number Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Darwin ARM64 uses identical syscall numbers to Darwin x86_64.
Note: Both share the XNU kernel syscalls.master table.
Note: All numbers include the 0x2000000 (33554432) Unix class prefix.

Note: 0x2000000 = 33554432

